{"id":"2007.12594","submitter":"Yiming Zhang","authors":"Yiming Zhang and Junguang Huang and Yong Yuan and Herbert Mang","title":"Direct dissipation-based arc-length approach for the cracking elements\n  method","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.CE","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Dissipated energy, representing a monotonically increasing state variable in\nnonlinear fracture mechanics, can be used as a restraint for tracing the\ndissipation instead of the elastic unloading path of the structure response. In\nthis work, in contrast to other energy-based approaches that use internal\nenergy and the work done by the external loads, a novel arc-length approach is\nproposed. It directly extracts the dissipated energy based on crack openings\nand tractions (displacement jumps and cohesive forces between two surfaces of\none crack), taking advantage of the global/extended method of cracking\nelements. Its linearized form is developed, and the stiffness factor of the\narc-length restraint is naturally obtained by means of the Sherman-Morrison\nformula. Once cohesive cracks appear, the proposed approach can be applied\nuntil most of the fracture energy is dissipated. Results from several numerical\ntests, in which arc-length control and self-propagating cracks are jointly\nused, are presented. They demonstrate the robustness of the proposed method,\nwhich captures both global and local peak loads and all snap-back parts of the\nforce-displacement responses of loaded structures with multiple cracks.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 4 Jul 2020 08:14:50 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-07-27"}
